commit again, it still outputs: 
'✖ prettier --write:
[error] Explicitly specified pattern "/Users/lilywu/github/angular-challenges/.github/agents/speckit.testing-helper.inspect.agent.md" is a symbolic link.'
which means prettier was asked to format a symbolic link (symlink), but it doesn't support formatting symlinks. As a result, lint-staged failed and 
the Git commit was aborted. 

A symbolic link (or symlink) is similar to a shortcut in Windows. It is a special type of file that points to another file or directory instead of 
storing the actual content itself.
say,
.github/agents/
└── speckit.testing-helper.inspect.agent.md
        │
        └────────► ../../.specify/extensions/testing-helper/agents/inspect.agent.md
The actual file is located elsewhere: ../../.specify/extensions/testing-helper/agents/inspect.agent.md
The file under .github/agents/ is not a real copy of the file. It is just a symbolic link that points to the actual file.
This means that when you open or edit the file through the symlink, you are actually accessing the original file it points to. 
Any changes are made to the original file, not to a separate copy.

Why does Prettier report an error?
because package.json contains the following lint-staged configuration:
"lint-staged": {
  "*.{ts,json,md}": [
    "prettier --write"
  ]
}
when you run 'git commit', the pre-commit hook triggers lint-staged, which passes all staged .ts, .json, and .md files to: $ prettier --write
one of those staged files is: .github/agents/speckit.testing-helper.inspect.agent.md
which is a symbolic link (symlink) rather than a regular file.
since prettier does not support formatting symlinks, it reports an error, causing lint-staged to fail and the Git commit to be aborted.

how to verify it's a symlink: 
$ ls -l .github/agents
if outputs are like speckit.testing-helper.inspect.agent.md -> ../../.specify/extensions/testing-helper/agents/inspect.agent.md
the -> indicates that the file is a symbolic link pointing to another file, rather than an actual file itself. That's why Prettier refuses to format it.

solution:
in package.json:
"lint-staged": {
  "*.{ts,json,md}": [
    "prettier --write"
  ]
}
edit to:    
"lint-staged": {
  "spec-kit-testing-extension/**/*.{ts,json,md}": [
    "prettier --write"
  ]
}
in this way, it only formats files under spec-kit-testing-extension/, it doesnt edit files under .github/agents/

